    <annotation>
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="head">
                    <marginalia_text>Duo fundamenta Romana[e] magnitudinis: vnum à Romulo humanum: alterum à Numa diuinum. Iacto Numa[e] necessario fundamento, eccè Armis deinceps geritur res: et sufficit vnus Numa, inter tot Romulos. 
                        Certè domi Temperantia, et Iustitia; foris Fortitudine; ubiq[ue] Prudentia, increscebat res Romana.
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Romulus"/>
                    <person name="Numa Pompilius"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>There are two foundations of Roman greatness: first a human one by Romulus, second a divine one by Numa. See how once Numa’s indispensable 
                foundation is thrown out, one acts with arms from then on; and between so many Romuluses one Numa suffices. Surely at home the Roman state became 
                stronger through restraint and justice, abroad through courage, and in all circumstances through prudence.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="right_margin">
                    <marginalia_text>An illam pacem, qua[e] sub Numa[e] regno fuit, Deos pra[e]stitisse credendum sit. August. l. 3. c. 9. An optandu[m], quod tanta belloru[m] rabie Romanoru[m] augeretur imperiu[m], cum eo studio, quo sub Numa auctum est, et quietum esse potuit, et tutum. 
                        L. eod. c. 10. De libris Numa[e], quos Senatus iussit incendi, ne sacroru[m] causa[e], quales in eis habebantur, innotescerent. l. 7. c. 34. De hydromantia, per qua[m] Numa, visis quibusdam Daemonum imaginibus, Ludificabatur. l. eod. c. 35. 
                        Vbi de Necroma[n]tia, seu Necyomantia. Et ibi L. Viues multa strictissimè. ) Libri autem Numa[e], qui fuerint, et qua[e] continerent: eccè apud Plinium l. 13. c. 13. Vnde veteru[m] secreta nonnihil detecta et praesertim philosophia[e] Pythagorica[e] arcana.</marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Numa Pompilius"/>
                    <person name="Augustine"/>
                    <person name="Juan Luis Vives"/>
                    <person name="Pliny the Elder"/>
                    <person name="Pythagoras"/>
                    <book title="De Civitate Dei"/>
                    <book title="Natural History"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>Whether we are to believe that the peace which prevailed during the reign of Numa was due to the protection of the gods: Augustine, bk. 3, c. 9. Whether it was desirable for the Roman empire to be increased by such a frenzy of warfare when it could have remained quiet 
                and secure by the policy that was pursued under Numa: the same book, c. 10. Of the books of Numa Pompilius, which the Senate ordered to be burned lest the reasons for the sacred rites described in them should become known: bk. 7, c. 34. Of hydromancy, 
                by which Numa was deluded when he saw certain images of the demons: the same book, c. 35. At which place [he writes] about Necromancy, or Necyomantia. At that place Juan Luis Vives also provides much information in the most rigorous way. 
                Yet as for what were Numa’s books and what they contained, see Pliny bk. 13, c. 13. Yet as for what were Numa’s books and what they contained, see Pliny bk. 13, c. 13, where the secrets of the ancients are somewhat revealed and especially the mysteries of 
                Pythagorean philosophy.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position book_orientation="0" place="right_margin">
                    <marginalia_text>Hactenùs Numa[e] Historia. Quem Plutarchus scitè vocat philosophum.
                    </marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Numa Pompilius"/>
                    <person name="Plutarch"/>
                    <emphasis method="pen" text="Historia. Quem Plutarchus scite" type="curved"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>So far the story of Numa, whom Plutarch expertly calls a philosopher.</translation>
        </marginalia>
        
